    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-11-13T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-11-13T10:00:00-05:00" n="1077"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1077">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5231/601: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-11-13T15:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 13, 1931—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:09 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>95. My No. 94, November 13, noon. I telegraph for your assistance in considering
                    this question, translation [of] a memorandum handed me at the Foreign
                    Office.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“By the commercial arrangement of August 1, 1906,<note n="13"
                            xml:id="d1077fn13">
                            <ref target="frus1906p2#pg_1342">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1906, pt. 2, p.
                            1342</ref>.</note> there was conceded to the United States the enjoyment
                        of the customs tariffs then established in our second column.</p>
                    <p>By the exchange of notes of December 20, 1906,<note n="14" xml:id="d1077fn14"
                            >Malloy, <hi rend="italic">Treaties, Conventions, etc.</hi>, 1776–1909,
                            vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 1719.</note> this treatment was
                        explained in the sense that reductions which might be conceded to a third
                        power would be applied also to the United States.</p>
                    <p>By the exchange of notes of October 6 and 21 [<hi rend="italic">22</hi>],
                            1923,<note n="15" xml:id="d1077fn15">
                            <ref target="frus1923v02#pg_873">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1923, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 873</ref>.</note> there was
                        conceded to the United States treatment provided by the agreement of August
                        1, 1906; but not the benefits which Spain in the future should grant to a
                        third power, thus modifying in this sense the agreement of August 1, 1906
                        and the exchange of notes of December 20, 1906.</p>
                    <p>By the Royal Decree of May 25, 1927 the Government of Spain conceded (a
                        unilateral measure) to the United States the treatment of greatest favor
                        resulting from the application of the commercial treaties which at that time
                        embodied consolidated tariffs and as long as those consolidations should
                        prevail. This treatment was granted for a maximum period of 6 months.</p>
                    <p>By an order of the Ministry of State dated November 7, 1927<note n="16"
                            xml:id="d1077fn16">
                            <ref target="frus1927v03#pg_733">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 1927, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps"
                                    >iii</hi>, p. 733</ref>.</note> the Royal Decree of May 25, 1927
                        was extended provisionally.</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Summary</hi>. Consequently as far as Spain is concerned
                        the Royal Decree of May 25, 1927 continues in force. Should the decree of
                        May 25, 1927 be annulled the commercial regime of both countries would again
                        become that which was agreed upon by both parties in the exchange of notes
                        of October 6 and 22, 1923.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>The summary should be read with the fact in mind that the consolidations were
                    abolished by decree of December 30 [<hi rend="italic">28</hi>], 1928.<note
                        n="17" xml:id="d1077fn17">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gaceta de Madrid</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>,
                        p. 2073.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
